  • File C:\Program Files (x86)\Steam\v8.dll has weak permissions: ALLOW BUILTIN\Users: FILE_WRITE_DATA FILE_APPEND_DATA DELETE WRITE_DAC WRITE_OWNER
  • File C:\Program Files (x86)\Steam\video.dll has weak permissions: ALLOW BUILTIN\Users: FILE_WRITE_DATA FILE_APPEND_DATA DELETE WRITE_DAC WRITE_OWNER
  • File C:\Program Files (x86)\Steam\VkLayer_steam_fossilize.dll has weak permissions: ALLOW BUILTIN\Users: FILE_WRITE_DATA FILE_APPEND_DATA DELETE WRITE_DAC WRITE_OWNER
  • File C:\Program Files (x86)\Steam\VkLayer_steam_fossilize64.dll has weak permissions: ALLOW BUILTIN\Users: FILE_WRITE_DATA FILE_APPEND_DATA DELETE WRITE_DAC WRITE_OWNER

  • File C:\Python27 has weak permissions: ALLOW BUILTIN\Users: FILE_ADD_FILE
recommendation

Service Can Be Reconfigured By Non-Admin Users

ImpactVery High
Ease of exploitationHigh
ConfidenceVery High
description

The service-level permissions on some Windows services allow them to be reconfigured by non-administrative users. This should not normally be required and is inherently insecure. It could certain users alter the program which is run when this service start and to alter which user the service runs as. The most likely attack would be to reconfigure the service to run as LocalSystem with no password and to select a malicious executable. This would give the attacker administrator level access to the local system.

The SERVICE_CHANGE_CONFIG permission has been granted to the following non-administrative users:

  • Windows Audio (Audiosrv) which runs as NT AUTHORITY\LocalService has permission granted for: [unknown]\S-1-5-32-549
  • Cryptographic Services (CryptSvc) which runs as NT Authority\NetworkService has permission granted for: [unknown]\S-1-5-32-549
  • Resultant Set of Policy Provider (RSoPProv) which runs as LocalSystem has permission granted for: [unknown]\S-1-5-32-549
  • SSDP Discovery (SSDPSRV) which runs as NT AUTHORITY\LocalService has permission granted for: [unknown]\S-1-5-32-549
  • UPnP Device Host (upnphost) which runs as NT AUTHORITY\LocalService has permission granted for: [unknown]\S-1-5-32-549
recommendation

Review the service-level permissions that have been granted to non-administrative users and revoke access where possible.

Untrusted Users Can Modify Windows Service Executables

ImpactHigh
Ease of exploitationVery High
ConfidenceVery High
description

Some of the programs that are run when Windows Services start were found to have weak file permissions. It is possible for non-administrative local users to replace some of the Windows Service executables with malicious programs. This could be abused to execute programs with the privileges of the Windows services concerned.

The programs below have FILE_WRITE, WRITE_DAC or WRITE_OWNER permission granted to non-administrative users:

  • UplayService (UplayService) runs the following program as LocalSystem:
  • C:\Program Files (x86)\Ubisoft\Ubisoft Game Launcher\UplayService.exe: ALLOW BUILTIN\Users: FILE_WRITE_DATA WRITE_OWNER WRITE_DAC
  • UplayWebCore (UplayWebCore) runs the following program as LocalSystem:
  • C:\Program Files (x86)\Ubisoft\Ubisoft Game Launcher\UplayWebCore.exe: ALLOW BUILTIN\Users: FILE_WRITE_DATA WRITE_OWNER WRITE_DAC
recommendation

Modify the permissions on the above programs to allow only administrators write access. Revoke write access from low-privileged users.

Insecure Permissions on Program Files

ImpactHigh
Ease of exploitationVery High
ConfidenceVery High
description

Some of the programs in %ProgramFiles% and/or %ProgramFiles(x86)% could be changed by non-administrative users. This could allow certain users on the system to place malicious code into certain key directories, or to replace programs with malicious ones. A malicious local user could use this technique to hijack the privileges of other local users, running commands with their privileges.

The directories below can be changed by non-administrative users:

  • File C:\Program Files (x86)\Rockstar Games has weak permissions: ALLOW BASEGAMESEAT-GR\kiosk: FILE_ADD_FILE FILE_ADD_SUBDIRECTORY FILE_WRITE_EA FILE_DELETE_CHILD FILE_WRITE_ATTRIBUTES DELETE WRITE_DAC WRITE_OWNER
  • File C:\Program Files (x86)\Rockstar Games has weak permissions: ALLOW BASEGAMESEAT-GR\kiosk: FILE_ADD_FILE FILE_ADD_SUBDIRECTORY FILE_WRITE_EA FILE_DELETE_CHILD FILE_WRITE_ATTRIBUTES DELETE WRITE_DAC WRITE_OWNER
  • File C:\Program Files (x86)\Rockstar Games has weak permissions: ALLOW BASEGAMESEAT-GR\kiosk: FILE_ADD_FILE FILE_ADD_SUBDIRECTORY FILE_WRITE_EA FILE_DELETE_CHILD FILE_WRITE_ATTRIBUTES DELETE WRITE_DAC WRITE_OWNER
  • File C:\Program Files (x86)\Rockstar Games has weak permissions: ALLOW BASEGAMESEAT-GR\kiosk: FILE_ADD_FILE FILE_ADD_SUBDIRECTORY FILE_WRITE_EA FILE_DELETE_CHILD FILE_WRITE_ATTRIBUTES DELETE WRITE_DAC WRITE_OWNER
recommendation

Programs run by multiple users should only be changable only by administrative users. The directories containing these programs should only be changable only by administrators too. Revoke write privileges for non-administrative users from the above programs and directories.

Windows Service Has Insecurely Quoted Path

ImpactHigh
Ease of exploitationVery High
ConfidenceMedium
description

The path to the executable for the service contains one or more spaces and quotes have not been correctly used around the path. The path is therefore ambiguous which could result in the wrong program being executed when the service is started - e.g. "C:\program.exe" instead of "C:\program files\foo\bar.exe". The issue is not necessarily exploitable unless a local attacker has permissions to add an alternative executable to the correct location on the filesystem. The impact of the issue should be considered higher for services that run with high privileges.

The following services have insecurely quoted paths:

  • UplayService (UplayService) runs as LocalSystem and has path: C:\Program Files (x86)\Ubisoft\Ubisoft Game Launcher\UplayService.exe:
  • UplayWebCore (UplayWebCore) runs as LocalSystem and has path: C:\Program Files (x86)\Ubisoft\Ubisoft Game Launcher\UplayWebCore.exe:
  • BattlEye Service (BEService) runs as LocalSystem and has path: C:\Program Files (x86)\Common Files\BattlEye\BEService.exe:
recommendation

Use quotes around the path to executables if they contain spaces: C:\program files\foo\bar.exe -> "C:\program files\foo\bar.exe".

Service Permissions Can Be Altered By Non-Admin Users

ImpactVery High
Ease of exploitationMedium
ConfidenceVery High
description

The service-level permissions on some Windows services allow some non-administrative users to set any service-level permissions of their choosing. This should not normally be required and is inherently insecure. It has a similar effect to granting the user DELETE and SERVICE_CHANGE_CONFIG. These powerful rights could allow the user to reconfigure a service to provide them with administrator level access, or simply to delete the service, disrupting normal business operations.

The WRITE_DAC permission has been granted to the following non-administrative users:

  • Windows Audio (Audiosrv) which runs as NT AUTHORITY\LocalService has permission granted for: [unknown]\S-1-5-32-549
  • Cryptographic Services (CryptSvc) which runs as NT Authority\NetworkService has permission granted for: [unknown]\S-1-5-32-549
  • Resultant Set of Policy Provider (RSoPProv) which runs as LocalSystem has permission granted for: [unknown]\S-1-5-32-549
  • SSDP Discovery (SSDPSRV) which runs as NT AUTHORITY\LocalService has permission granted for: [unknown]\S-1-5-32-549
  • UPnP Device Host (upnphost) which runs as NT AUTHORITY\LocalService has permission granted for: [unknown]\S-1-5-32-549
recommendation

Review the service-level permissions that have been granted to non-administrative users and revoke access where possible.

Non-Admin Users Can Take Ownership of Service

ImpactVery High
Ease of exploitationMedium
ConfidenceVery High
description

The service-level permissions on some Windows services allow ownership to be claimed by some non-administrative users. This should not normally be required and is inherently insecure. It has a similar effect to granting the user WRITE_DAC (and thus DELETE and SERVICE_CHANGE_CONFIG). These powerful rights could allow the user to reconfigure a service to provide them with administrator level access, or simply to delete the service, disrupting normal business operations.

The WRITE_OWNER permission has been granted to the following non-administrative users:

  • Windows Audio (Audiosrv) which runs as NT AUTHORITY\LocalService has permission granted for: [unknown]\S-1-5-32-549
  • Cryptographic Services (CryptSvc) which runs as NT Authority\NetworkService has permission granted for: [unknown]\S-1-5-32-549
  • Resultant Set of Policy Provider (RSoPProv) which runs as LocalSystem has permission granted for: [unknown]\S-1-5-32-549
  • SSDP Discovery (SSDPSRV) which runs as NT AUTHORITY\LocalService has permission granted for: [unknown]\S-1-5-32-549
  • UPnP Device Host (upnphost) which runs as NT AUTHORITY\LocalService has permission granted for: [unknown]\S-1-5-32-549
recommendation

Review the service-level permissions that have been granted to non-administrative users and revoke access where possible.

Non-Admin Can Change File Paths In Registry

ImpactMedium
Ease of exploitationVery High
ConfidenceLow
description

A walk of the registry found some registry keys that can be changed by non-admin users (KEY_SET_VALUE permission). The data in some of those keys appears to be a file or directory path (e.g. c:\..., \host\share, \.\pipe\...). This is a simple regular-expression match so may report false positives. In some instances it may be possible for an low-privilged user to cause other users to follow a malicious UNC file path, forcing disclosure of their netntlm password hash or SMB relay attack. Other path-based attacks may also be possible.

  • ALLOW [unknown]\S-1-5-80-3981856537-581775623-1136376035-2066872258-409572886: KEY_SET_VALUE
  • Registry value HKEY_LOCAL_MACHINE\SYSTEM\CurrentControlSet\Services\W32Time\TimeProviders\NtpClient\DllName has data ''%systemroot%\\system32\\w32time.dll'' and permissions:
  • ALLOW NT SERVICE\W32Time: KEY_SET_VALUE
  • Registry value HKEY_LOCAL_MACHINE\SYSTEM\CurrentControlSet\Services\W32Time\TimeProviders\NtpServer\DllName has data ''%systemroot%\\system32\\w32time.dll'' and permissions:
  • ALLOW NT SERVICE\W32Time: KEY_SET_VALUE
  • Registry value HKEY_LOCAL_MACHINE\SYSTEM\CurrentControlSet\Services\W32Time\TimeProviders\VMICTimeProvider\DllName has data ''%SystemRoot%\\System32\\vmictimeprovider.dll'' and permissions:
  • ALLOW NT SERVICE\W32Time: KEY_SET_VALUE
  • Registry value HKEY_LOCAL_MACHINE\SYSTEM\CurrentControlSet\Services\W32Time\TimeProviders\VMICTimeProvider\DllName has data ''%SystemRoot%\\System32\\vmictimeprovider.dll'' and permissions:
  • ALLOW NT SERVICE\vmictimesync: KEY_SET_VALUE
recommendation

Set strong registry permissions on any values that high privileged processes use to determine paths.

Non-Admin Can Change Registry Paths That Are Stored In The Registry

ImpactMedium
Ease of exploitationVery High
ConfidenceLow
description

A walk of the registry found some registry keys that can be changed by non-admin users (KEY_SET_VALUE permission). The data in some of those keys appears to be a registry path (e.g. SYSTEM\...). This is a simple regular-expression match so may report false positives. In some instances it may be possible for an low-privilged user to cause other users to follow read malicious data from the registry. The may or may not lead to privilege escalation depending on the context.

The following registry value are affected:

  • Registry value HKEY_LOCAL_MACHINE\SOFTWARE\Microsoft\PLA\Report has data ''system\\System Diagnostics'' and permissions:
  • ALLOW BASEGAMESEAT-GR\kiosk: KEY_SET_VALUE
  • Registry value HKEY_LOCAL_MACHINE\SYSTEM\ControlSet001\Services\Dhcp\Parameters\Options\46\RegLocation has data ''SYSTEM\\CurrentControlSet\\Services\\NetBT\\Parameters\\DhcpNodeType'' and permissions:
  • ALLOW NT SERVICE\Dhcp: KEY_SET_VALUE
  • Registry value HKEY_LOCAL_MACHINE\SYSTEM\ControlSet001\Services\Dhcp\Parameters\Options\47\RegLocation has data ''SYSTEM\\CurrentControlSet\\Services\\NetBT\\Parameters\\DhcpScopeID'' and permissions:
  • ALLOW NT SERVICE\Dhcp: KEY_SET_VALUE
  • Registry value HKEY_LOCAL_MACHINE\SYSTEM\ControlSet002\Services\Dhcp\Parameters\Options\46\RegLocation has data ''SYSTEM\\CurrentControlSet\\Services\\NetBT\\Parameters\\DhcpNodeType'' and permissions:
  • ALLOW NT SERVICE\Dhcp: KEY_SET_VALUE
  • Registry value HKEY_LOCAL_MACHINE\SYSTEM\ControlSet002\Services\Dhcp\Parameters\Options\47\RegLocation has data ''SYSTEM\\CurrentControlSet\\Services\\NetBT\\Parameters\\DhcpScopeID'' and permissions:
  • ALLOW NT SERVICE\Dhcp: KEY_SET_VALUE
  • Registry value HKEY_LOCAL_MACHINE\SYSTEM\CurrentControlSet\Services\Dhcp\Parameters\Options\46\RegLocation has data ''SYSTEM\\CurrentControlSet\\Services\\NetBT\\Parameters\\DhcpNodeType'' and permissions:
  • ALLOW NT SERVICE\Dhcp: KEY_SET_VALUE
  • Registry value HKEY_LOCAL_MACHINE\SYSTEM\CurrentControlSet\Services\Dhcp\Parameters\Options\47\RegLocation has data ''SYSTEM\\CurrentControlSet\\Services\\NetBT\\Parameters\\DhcpScopeID'' and permissions:
  • ALLOW NT SERVICE\Dhcp: KEY_SET_VALUE
recommendation

Set strong registry permissions on any values that high privileged processes use to determine registry paths.

Windows Service Registry Keys Allow Untrusted Users To Create Subkeys

ImpactMedium
Ease of exploitationVery High
ConfidenceVery Low
description

Configuration information for Windows Service is stored in the registry. Some of the keys were found to have the KEY_CREATE_SUB_KEY permission granted for non-administrative users. It may be possible for low privileged users to manipulate service - though this would depend on how the service responded to the addition of new registry keys.

The registry keys below had KEY_CREATE_SUB_KEY granted for non-administrative users:

  • DHCP Client (Dhcp) uses registry key HKEY_LOCAL_MACHINE\SYSTEM\CurrentControlSet\Services\Dhcp:
  • HKEY_LOCAL_MACHINE\SYSTEM\CurrentControlSet\Services\Dhcp: ALLOW NT SERVICE\Dhcp: KEY_CREATE_SUB_KEY
recommendation

Review the permissions of keys with KEY_CREATE_SUB_KEY granged. Revoke KEY_CREATE_SUB_KEY permissions for non-administrative users where possible.

Executables for Running Processes Can Be Modified On Disk

ImpactHigh
Ease of exploitationMedium
ConfidenceVery High
description

The file permissions for the processes running at the time of the audit were checked. The executables for some of the processes could be replaced by non-administrative users. This could enable an attacker to escalate privilege to the owner of the processes concerned. An attacker would need to replace the program on disk and wait for the program to be run again as the user concerned.

The following files could be replaced by non-administrative users (TODO: how?):

  • Process ID 2604 (C:\Program Files (x86)\steam\steam.exe) as weak permissions. TODO: Weak how?
  • Process ID 4740 (G:\Asgard\GameLibrary\100021711\build\bin\cef\cef.win7\steamwebhelper.exe) as weak permissions. TODO: Weak how?
  • Process ID 1492 (G:\Asgard\GameLibrary\100021711\build\bin\cef\cef.win7\steamwebhelper.exe) as weak permissions. TODO: Weak how?
  • Process ID 4784 (G:\Asgard\GameLibrary\100021711\build\bin\cef\cef.win7\steamwebhelper.exe) as weak permissions. TODO: Weak how?
  • Process ID 1308 (G:\Asgard\GameLibrary\100021711\build\bin\cef\cef.win7\steamwebhelper.exe) as weak permissions. TODO: Weak how?
  • Process ID 2588 (G:\Asgard\GameLibrary\100021711\build\bin\cef\cef.win7\steamwebhelper.exe) as weak permissions. TODO: Weak how?
  • Process ID 5132 (C:\Program Files (x86)\steam\GameOverlayUI.exe) as weak permissions. TODO: Weak how?
  • Process ID 4292 (G:\Asgard\GameLibrary\100021711\build\bin\cef\cef.win7\steamwebhelper.exe) as weak permissions. TODO: Weak how?
  • Process ID 7528 (C:\Program Files (x86)\Steam\steamapps\workshop\content\304930\1785308600\Explorer++.exe) as weak permissions. TODO: Weak how?
  • Process ID 6960 (C:\windows-privesc-check-master\windows-privesc-check2.exe) as weak permissions. TODO: Weak how?
  • Process ID 6688 (C:\windows-privesc-check-master\windows-privesc-check2.exe) as weak permissions. TODO: Weak how?
recommendation

Set strong file permissions on each of the programs below. Also set strong file permissions on parent directories. Ideally only administrative users would have the ability to change programs run by multiple users. Note that this issue can usually be considered a false positive is users are simply running programs from their home directory - provided that no other non-admin users can modify them.

SMB Server Does Not Mandate Packet Signing

ImpactHigh
Ease of exploitationMedium
ConfidenceVery High
description

SMB clients that connect to this server are not forced to use signing. As signing protects data from modification in transit, clients may end up receiving data that has been maliciously altered by an attacker. This could lead to a compromise of the client if it opens or runs the files accessed - particularly in the case of a domain member access group policy information.

The following registry key shows the current policy setting:

  • Reg key: HKEY_LOCAL_MACHINE\System\CurrentControlSet\Services\LanManServer\Parameters\RequireSecuritySignature, Value: 0
recommendation

Set the security policy setting 'Microsoft network server: Digitally sign communications (always)' to Enabled.

SMB Client Does Not Mandate Packet Signing

ImpactHigh
Ease of exploitationMedium
ConfidenceVery High
description

SMB connection originating from this host might not negotiate pack signing. As signing protects data from modification in transit, clients may end up sending or receiving data that has been maliciously altered by an attacker. This could lead to a compromise of the client or server.

The following registry key shows the current policy setting:

  • Reg key: HKEY_LOCAL_MACHINE\System\CurrentControlSet\Services\LanmanWorkstation\Parameters\RequireSecuritySignature, Value: 0
recommendation

Set the security policy setting 'Microsoft network server: Digitally sign communications (always)' to Enabled.

Context Handler Menus Use Poorly Protected Files

ImpactHigh
Ease of exploitationMedium
ConfidenceHigh
description

Context Menus appear in Windows Explorer when files are right-clicked. Each has a corresponding DLL or .EXE. Some of the referenced DLLs or .EXE file can be replaced by non-administrative users. As these context menus are used by all system users, there is a possibility that a user might run malicious code of an attacker's choosing if the DLLs or .EXEs are modified. DragDrop Handlers Use Poorly Protected Files

ImpactHigh
Ease of exploitationMedium
ConfidenceHigh
description

"DragDrop Handlers" are a type of Windows Explorer shell extension that determine behaviour when files or folders are dragged and dropped. Each as a corresponding DLL or .EXE. Some of DLLs or .EXEs used can be replaced by non-administrative users. As DragDrop Handlers are used by all system users, there is a possibility that a user might run malicious code of an attacker's choosing if the DLLs or .EXEs are modified. Vulnerable Software Version Installed

ImpactHigh
Ease of exploitationMedium
ConfidenceMedium
description

The version numbers of some installed software were compared against an internal list of version numbers known to have vulnerabilities. Some installed version were equal to or older than the vulnerable versions. This issue is extremely prone to false negatives because not all software is checked and the internal list of vulnerable versions quickly becomes outdated. The vulnerabilities affecting the software below are not necessarily high risk. This issue simply reports that at least one security issue exists.

The following vulnerable versions of software were installed:

  • Wireshark 1.8.7 (64-bit) (v1.8.7) by The Wireshark developer community, http://www.wireshark.org (last updated: None) <= v1.8.7
recommendation

Manually look up the known security issues corresponding to the versions installed.

Share Level Permissions Allow Access By Non-Admin Users

ImpactLow
Ease of exploitationVery High
ConfidenceVery High
description

The share-level permissions on some Windows file shares allows access by non-administrative users. This can often be desirable, in which case this issue can be ignored. However, sometimes it can allow data to be stolen or programs to be maliciously modified. NB: Setting strong NTFS permissions can sometimes mean that data which seems to be exposed on a share actually isn't accessible.
recommendation

Review the share-level permissions that have been granted to non-administrative users and revoke access where possible. Share-level permissions can be viewed in Windows Explorer: Right-click folder | Sharing and Security | "Sharing" tab | "Permissions" button (for XP - other OSs may vary slightly).

Service Can Be Started By Non-Admin Users

ImpactLow
Ease of exploitationVery High
ConfidenceVery High
description

The service-level permissions on some Windows services allow them to be started by non-administrative users. This can often be desirable, in which case this issue can be ignored. However, sometimes it can allow users to expose or exploit a vulnerability connected with the service - e.g. it may listen on the network or it may have been tampered with by an attacker and they now need to start the service. The permission is not always dangerous on its own, but can sometimes aid a local attacker.

The SERVICE_START permission has been granted to the following non-administrative users:

  • Application Information (Appinfo) which runs as LocalSystem has permission granted for: NT AUTHORITY\INTERACTIVE
  • Application Management (AppMgmt) which runs as LocalSystem has permission granted for: NT AUTHORITY\INTERACTIVE
  • AppX Deployment Service (AppXSVC) (AppXSvc) which runs as LocalSystem has permission granted for: APPLICATION PACKAGE AUTHORITY\ALL APPLICATION PACKAGES
  • AppX Deployment Service (AppXSVC) (AppXSvc) which runs as LocalSystem has permission granted for: NT AUTHORITY\INTERACTIVE
  • AppX Deployment Service (AppXSVC) (AppXSvc) which runs as LocalSystem has permission granted for: NT AUTHORITY\SERVICE
  • Windows Audio (Audiosrv) which runs as NT AUTHORITY\LocalService has permission granted for: [unknown]\S-1-5-32-549
  • Background Tasks Infrastructure Service (BrokerInfrastructure) which runs as LocalSystem has permission granted for: BUILTIN\Users
  • Certificate Propagation (CertPropSvc) which runs as LocalSystem has permission granted for: NT SERVICE\TermService
  • Cryptographic Services (CryptSvc) which runs as NT Authority\NetworkService has permission granted for: [unknown]\S-1-5-32-549
  • DHCP Client (Dhcp) which runs as NT Authority\LocalService has permission granted for: \CONSOLE LOGON
  • Device Setup Manager (DsmSvc) which runs as LocalSystem has permission granted for: BUILTIN\Users
  • Encrypting File System (EFS) (EFS) which runs as LocalSystem has permission granted for: NT AUTHORITY\INTERACTIVE
  • Encrypting File System (EFS) (EFS) which runs as LocalSystem has permission granted for: NT AUTHORITY\SERVICE

Service Can Be Stopped By Non-Admin Users

ImpactLow
Ease of exploitationVery High
ConfidenceVery High
description

The service-level permissions on some Windows services allow them to be stopped by non-administrative users. This can often be desirable, in which case this issue can be ignored. However, sometimes it can allow users to evade monitoring services - e.g. Anti-virus. This permission can also be required in order to exploit other weaknesses such as weak file permissions on service executables. The permission is not always dangerous on its own, but can sometimes aid a local attacker.

The SERVICE_STOP permission has been granted to the following non-administrative users:

  • Windows Audio (Audiosrv) which runs as NT AUTHORITY\LocalService has permission granted for: [unknown]\S-1-5-32-549
  • Certificate Propagation (CertPropSvc) which runs as LocalSystem has permission granted for: NT SERVICE\TermService
  • Cryptographic Services (CryptSvc) which runs as NT Authority\NetworkService has permission granted for: [unknown]\S-1-5-32-549
  • Network Access Protection Agent (napagent) which runs as NT AUTHORITY\NetworkService has permission granted for: NT AUTHORITY\NETWORK SERVICE
  • Resultant Set of Policy Provider (RSoPProv) which runs as LocalSystem has permission granted for: [unknown]\S-1-5-32-549
  • Smart Card Device Enumeration Service (ScDeviceEnum) which runs as LocalSystem has permission granted for: NT SERVICE\ScDeviceEnum
  • Remote Desktop Configuration (SessionEnv) which runs as localSystem has permission granted for: NT SERVICE\TermService
  • Remote Desktop Configuration (SessionEnv) which runs as localSystem has permission granted for: [unknown]\S-1-5-80-4130899010-3337817248-2959896732-3640118089-1866760602
  • Internet Connection Sharing (ICS) (SharedAccess) which runs as LocalSystem has permission granted for: NT AUTHORITY\SERVICE
  • SSDP Discovery (SSDPSRV) which runs as NT AUTHORITY\LocalService has permission granted for: [unknown]\S-1-5-32-549
  • SSDP Discovery (SSDPSRV) which runs as NT AUTHORITY\LocalService has permission granted for: NT AUTHORITY\LOCAL SERVICE
  • SSDP Discovery (SSDPSRV) which runs as NT AUTHORITY\LocalService has permission granted for: NT AUTHORITY\NETWORK SERVICE
  • Remote Desktop Services UserMode Port Redirector (UmRdpService) which runs as localSystem has permission granted for: NT SERVICE\TermService
  • UPnP Device Host (upnphost) which runs as NT AUTHORITY\LocalService has permission granted for: [unknown]\S-1-5-32-549
  • UPnP Device Host (upnphost) which runs as NT AUTHORITY\LocalService has permission granted for: NT AUTHORITY\LOCAL SERVICE
  • UPnP Device Host (upnphost) which runs as NT AUTHORITY\LocalService has permission granted for: NT AUTHORITY\NETWORK SERVICE
  • Windows Time (W32Time) which runs as NT AUTHORITY\LocalService has permission granted for: NT AUTHORITY\LOCAL SERVICE

Service Can Be Deleted By Non-Admin Users

ImpactLow
Ease of exploitationVery High
ConfidenceVery High
description

The service-level permissions on some Windows services allow them to be deleted by non-administrative users. This should not normally be required and is inherently insecure. It could allow local users to delete the service. This may allow them to evade monitor - e.g. from Anti-virus - or to disrupt normal business operations. Note that the user would not be able to replace the service as administrator level rights are required to create new services.

The DELETE permission has been granted to the following non-administrative users:

  • Windows Audio (Audiosrv) which runs as NT AUTHORITY\LocalService has permission granted for: [unknown]\S-1-5-32-549
  • Cryptographic Services (CryptSvc) which runs as NT Authority\NetworkService has permission granted for: [unknown]\S-1-5-32-549
  • Resultant Set of Policy Provider (RSoPProv) which runs as LocalSystem has permission granted for: [unknown]\S-1-5-32-549
  • SSDP Discovery (SSDPSRV) which runs as NT AUTHORITY\LocalService has permission granted for: [unknown]\S-1-5-32-549
  • UPnP Device Host (upnphost) which runs as NT AUTHORITY\LocalService has permission granted for: [unknown]\S-1-5-32-549
recommendation

Review the service-level permissions that have been granted to non-administrative users and revoke access where possible.

Non-Admin Can Change Usernames That Are Stored In The Registry

ImpactLow
Ease of exploitationVery High
ConfidenceMedium
description

A walk of the registry found some registry keys that can be changed by non-admin users (KEY_SET_VALUE permission). The data in some of those keys appears to be a username. This is a simple regular-expression match so may report false positives. In some instances it may be possible for an low-privilged user to cause another process to run as or otherwise affect a different user account.

Directory Creation Allowed On Drive Root

ImpactLow
Ease of exploitationHigh
ConfidenceVery High
description

Some of the local drive roots allow non-administrative users to create directories. This could provide attackers with a place to stash hacking tools, or proive legitimacy to malware they are seeking to get other users to run. It is relatively common to allow the creation of directories in the drive root, but it probably isn't required for normal operation. NB: This issue has only been reported for NTFS filesystems. Other non-NTFS file system may also allow this behaviour. A separate issue is reported for non-NTFS filesystems.

The following drives allow non-administrative users to create directories in to their root:

  • Drive A:\ allows BUILTIN\Users to add directories
  • Drive B:\ allows BUILTIN\Users to add directories
  • Drive C:\ allows BUILTIN\Users to add directories
  • Drive E:\ allows BUILTIN\Users to add directories
  • Drive F:\ allows BUILTIN\Users to add directories
  • Drive G:\ allows BUILTIN\Users to add directories
recommendation

Modify the permissions on the drive roots to only allow administrators to create directories. Revoke this permission from low-privileged users.

Current Working Directory Used For DLL Search - Including Network Locations

ImpactHigh
Ease of exploitationLow
ConfidenceHigh
description

CWDIllegalInDllSearch was set to 0. This causes applications (by default) to load DLLs from the current directory - even for network locations. This can lead to malicious DLLs being executed in some attack scenarios. Note that KB2264107 needs to be installed to enable more secure settings - not checked for. Also apps can be secured individually - also not checked for.

The following registry key shows the current policy setting:

  • Reg key: HKEY_LOCAL_MACHINE\SYSTEM\CurrentControlSet\Control\Session Manager\CWDIllegalInDllSearch, Value: None
recommendation

Consider setting CWDIllegalInDllSearch to 1, 2 or 0xFFFFFFFF to improve security - though this may break some applications. See http://support.microsoft.com/kb/2264107 for further information including how to set CWDIllegalInDllSearch on a per-application basis.

User Access Control Not Enabled

ImpactVery High
Ease of exploitationVery Low
ConfidenceVery High
description

UAC has been disabled on the system. It will not mitigate the compromise of administrative accounts. This is not the default configuration.

The following registry key shows the current policy setting:

  • Reg key: HKEY_LOCAL_MACHINE\SOFTWARE\Microsoft\Windows\CurrentVersion\Policies\System\EnableLUA, Value: 0
recommendation

Enable the security policy setting 'User Account Control: Run all administrators in Admin Approval Mode'.

Windows Service Executable Is Missing

ImpactVery Low
Ease of exploitationNot defined
ConfidenceVery High
description

Each Windows Service has a corresponding executable. The executables for some services were missing at the time of the audit. This can sometimes be caused programs being manually deleted instead of being properly uninstalled. Although this configuration is unusual and probably undesirable, it is unlikely to be a security issue unless an attacker can recreate the executables in question - an issue that was NOT checked for (please check manually). It may be an indication that an attacker has previously abused a Windows service and left it in a half-configured state, so investigating the cause of the problem is advised.

The following Windows Services has missing executables:

  • Password Changer (KioskPwdChanger) tries to run '"C:\Asgard\services\KioskPwdChanger\KioskPwdChangerService.exe"' as LocalSystem
  • nvcloudinit (nvcloudinit) tries to run 'c:\asgard\services\nvcloudinit\nvcloudinit.exe' as LocalSystem
  • winexesvc (winexesvc) tries to run 'winexesvc.exe' as LocalSystem
  • NVIDIA Masquerade service (nvmsqrdsvc) tries to run '"C:\Asgard\services\masquerade\nvmsqrdsvc.exe"' as LocalSystem
  • NVIDIA Grid Service (NvGridSvc) tries to run 'C:\Asgard\services\NvGridSvc\NvGridSvc.exe' as LocalSystem
recommendation

Investigate why the service is broken and either fix or remove the service as appropriate.

Scheduled Task Calls Non-Existent Program

ImpactNot defined
Ease of exploitationNot defined
ConfidenceNot defined
description

A Scheduled Task is configured to run a program that doesn't exist. This is not necessarily a security problem unless the file can be maliciously created. This issue gives false-positives for programs which aren't specified using their full path.

The following tasks were affected:

  • Task \EnableDefaultExplorerKiosk runs non-existent file C:\asgard\tools\gfndesktop\EnableDefaultExplorerKiosk.bat
  • Task \EnableGfnDesktopKiosk runs non-existent file C:\asgard\tools\gfndesktop\EnableGfnDesktopKiosk.bat
recommendation

Review affected Scheduled Tasks and disabled where approriate.

Windows Autologon Registry Keys Set

ImpactNot defined
Ease of exploitationNot defined
ConfidenceNot defined
description

One or more of the registry keys for Windows autologon was found to be set. These can explose locally valid logon credentials in cleartext.

The following information was retreived from the registry:

  • Registry key HKEY_LOCAL_MACHINE\SOFTWARE\Microsoft\Windows NT\CurrentVersion\Winlogon had these values set: AutoAdminLogon=1 DefaultDomainName=BASEGAMESEAT-GR DefaultUserName=kiosk DefaultPassword=[not set]
recommendation

Review the information below and determine if is exposes sensitive information. Avoid the use of autologin where possible.

WinRM Windows Remote Management (WS-Management) STARTED NT AUTHORITY\NetworkService Windows Remote Management (WinRM) service implements the WS-Management protocol for remote management. WS-Management is a standard web services protocol used for remote software and hardware management. The WinRM service listens on the network for WS-Management requests and processes them. The WinRM Service needs to be configured with a listener using winrm.cmd command line tool or through Group Policy in order for it to listen over the network. The WinRM service provides access to WMI data and enables event collection. Event collection and subscription to events require that the service is running. WinRM messages use HTTP and HTTPS as transports. The WinRM service does not depend on IIS but is preconfigured to share a port with IIS on the same machine. The WinRM service reserves the /wsman URL prefix. To prevent conflicts with IIS, administrators should ensure that any websites hosted on IIS do not use the /wsman URL prefix. C:\Windows\System32\svchost.exe

Rating Definitions

impact

Level Name Description
0N/AN/A
1Very LowHardly worth mentioning.
2LowNot necessarily interesting alone, but may help with other attacks.
3MediumUncertain impact / Impact doesn't relate to command executation.
4HighDirect access to another user account - may not be admin.
5Very HighDirectly get SYSTEM/Administrator privileges.

ease

Level Name Description
0N/AN/A
1Very LowVery complex to exploit / contrived or very unlikely exploitation scenarion.
2LowCustom code required.
3MediumNeeds standard tools to be uploaded for exploitation / needs user assistance (less probable).
4HighMultiple easy steps. Need to wait for exploit to trigger / user assistance (probable).
5Very HighCan be done easily with builtin tools. Low number of steps. No need for command line.

confidence

Level Name Description
0N/AN/A
1Very LowA lot more research is required to establish if the premise for the issue is correct and if exploitation would be viable in this instance.
2LowPremise for issue is probably right, but the check is unreliable, inaccurate or incomplete.
3MediumReasonable idea for an attack. Success will be situation dependent. Need to verify manually.
4HighStrong issue. Probably viable, but some pre-requisite conditions not checked.
5Very HighIssue described is likely to be 100% accurate.
